description: From Middle English ledes-man (“a military commander”, “a general”); equivalent to leads (the genitive form of lead: “a leading”, “a directing”, “a guiding”) + man.
From (genitive form of) lead (“heavy metal; Pb”) + man.

entries.meaning: (nautical) A sailor who takes soundings with a lead, measuring the depth of water.
examples: In the same moment the leadsman hove the lead, and, finding it directly take the ground, he, in his fright, called out, ‘There's only three fathom.’
